#: ../../../features.rst:-1
msgid ""
"An overview of the key features that distinguish Spack from other package "
"managers, including simple installation, custom configurations, and non-"
"destructive installs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:11
msgid "Feature Overview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:13
msgid ""
"This is a high-level overview of features that make Spack different from "
"other `package managers <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/"
"Package_management_system>`_ and `port systems <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/"
"Ports_collection>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:16
msgid "Simple package installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:18
msgid ""
"Installing the default version of a package is simple. This will install the "
"latest version of the ``mpileaks`` package and all of its dependencies:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:21
msgid "$ spack install mpileaks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:26
msgid "Custom versions & configurations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:28
msgid ""
"Spack allows installation to be customized. Users can specify the version, "
"compile-time options, and target architecture, all on the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:31
msgid ""
"# Install a particular version by appending @\n"
"$ spack install hdf5@1.14\n"
"\n"
"# Add special compile-time options by name\n"
"$ spack install hdf5@1.14 api=v110\n"
"\n"
"# Add special boolean compile-time options with +\n"
"$ spack install hdf5@1.14 +hl\n"
"\n"
"# Add compiler flags using the conventional names\n"
"$ spack install hdf5@1.14 cflags=\"-O3 -floop-block\"\n"
"\n"
"# Target a specific micro-architecture\n"
"$ spack install hdf5@1.14 target=icelake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:48
msgid ""
"Users can specify as many or as few options as they care about. Spack will "
"fill in the unspecified values with sensible defaults."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:52
msgid "Customize dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:54
msgid ""
"Spack allows *dependencies* of a particular installation to be customized "
"extensively. Users can specify both *direct* dependencies of a package, "
"using the ``%`` sigil, or *transitive* dependencies, using the ``^`` sigil:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:57
msgid ""
"# Install hdf5 using gcc@15 as a compiler (direct dependency of hdf5)\n"
"$ spack install hdf5@1.14 %gcc@15\n"
"\n"
"# Install hdf5 using hwloc with CUDA enabled (transitive dependency)\n"
"$ spack install hdf5@1.14 ^hwloc+cuda"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:65
msgid ""
"The expression on the command line can be as simple or as complicated as the "
"user needs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:67
msgid ""
"# Install hdf5 compiled with gcc@15, linked to mpich compiled with gcc@14\n"
"$ spack install hdf5@1.14 %gcc@15 ^mpich %gcc@14"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:73
msgid "Non-destructive installs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:75
msgid ""
"Spack installs every unique package/dependency configuration into its own "
"prefix, so new installs will not break existing ones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:78
msgid "Packages can peacefully coexist"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:80
msgid ""
"Spack avoids library misconfiguration by using ``RPATH`` to link "
"dependencies. When a user links a library or runs a program, it is tied to "
"the dependencies it was built with, so there is no need to manipulate "
"``LD_LIBRARY_PATH`` at runtime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:84
msgid "Unprivileged user installs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:86
msgid ""
"Spack does not require administrator privileges to install packages. You can "
"install software in any directory you choose, making it easy to manage "
"packages in your home directory or shared project locations without needing "
"sudo access."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:90
msgid "From source and binary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:92
msgid ""
"Spack's core strength is creating highly customized, optimized software "
"builds from source code. While it's primarily a from-source package manager, "
"it also supports fast binary installations through build caches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:96
msgid "Contributing is easy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:98
msgid ""
"To contribute a new package, all Spack needs is a URL for the source "
"archive. The ``spack create`` command will create a boilerplate package "
"file, and the package authors can fill in specific build steps in pure "
"Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:101
msgid "For example, this command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:103
msgid ""
"$ spack create https://ftp.osuosl.org/pub/blfs/conglomeration/libelf/"
"libelf-0.8.13.tar.gz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:107
msgid "creates a simple Python file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:109
msgid ""
"from spack.package import *\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class Libelf(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"    \"\"\"FIXME: Put a proper description of your package here.\"\"\"\n"
"\n"
"    # FIXME: Add a proper url for your package's homepage here.\n"
"    homepage = \"https://www.example.com\"\n"
"    url = \"https://ftp.osuosl.org/pub/blfs/conglomeration/libelf/"
"libelf-0.8.13.tar.gz\"\n"
"\n"
"    # FIXME: Add a list of GitHub accounts to\n"
"    # notify when the package is updated.\n"
"    # maintainers(\"github_user1\", \"github_user2\")\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"0.8.13\", "
"sha256=\"591a9b4ec81c1f2042a97aa60564e0cb79d041c52faa7416acb38bc95bd2c76d\")\n"
"\n"
"    # FIXME: Add dependencies if required.\n"
"    # depends_on(\"foo\")\n"
"\n"
"    def configure_args(self):\n"
"        # FIXME: Add arguments other than --prefix\n"
"        # FIXME: If not needed delete this function\n"
"        args = []\n"
"        return args"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:136
msgid ""
"It doesn't take much Python coding to get from there to a working package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:138
msgid ""
"from spack_repo.builtin.build_systems.autotools import AutotoolsPackage\n"
"\n"
"from spack.package import *\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class Libelf(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"    \"\"\"libelf lets you read, modify or create ELF object files in an\n"
"    architecture-independent way. The library takes care of size\n"
"    and endian issues, e.g. you can process a file for SPARC\n"
"    processors on an Intel-based system. Note: libelf is no longer\n"
"    maintained and packages that depend on libelf should migrate to\n"
"    elfutils.\"\"\"\n"
"\n"
"    # The original homepage no longer exists, but the tar file is\n"
"    # archived at fossies.org.\n"
"    # homepage = \"http://www.mr511.de/software/english.html\"\n"
"\n"
"    homepage = \"https://directory.fsf.org/wiki/Libelf\"\n"
"\n"
"    urls = [\n"
"        \"https://fossies.org/linux/misc/old/libelf-0.8.13.tar.gz\",\n"
"        \"https://ftp.osuosl.org/pub/blfs/conglomeration/libelf/"
"libelf-0.8.13.tar.gz\",\n"
"    ]\n"
"\n"
"    license(\"LGPL-2.0-only\")\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"0.8.13\", "
"sha256=\"591a9b4ec81c1f2042a97aa60564e0cb79d041c52faa7416acb38bc95bd2c76d\")\n"
"\n"
"    depends_on(\"c\", type=\"build\")  # generated\n"
"\n"
"    provides(\"elf@0\")\n"
"\n"
"    # configure: error: neither int nor long is 32-bit\n"
"    depends_on(\"automake\", when=\"platform=darwin\", type=\"build\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"autoconf\", when=\"platform=darwin\", type=\"build\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"libtool\", when=\"platform=darwin\", type=\"build\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"m4\", when=\"platform=darwin\", type=\"build\")\n"
"\n"
"    @property\n"
"    def force_autoreconf(self):\n"
"        return self.spec.satisfies(\"platform=darwin\")\n"
"\n"
"    def configure_args(self):\n"
"        args = [\"--enable-shared\", \"--disable-debug\"]\n"
"\n"
"        # config.sub: invalid option -apple-darwin21.6.0\n"
"        if self.spec.satisfies(\"platform=darwin target=aarch64:\"):\n"
"            args.append(\"--build=aarch64-apple-darwin\")\n"
"\n"
"        return args\n"
"\n"
"    def install(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"        make(\"install\", parallel=False)\n"
"\n"
"    def flag_handler(self, name, flags):\n"
"        if name == \"cflags\":\n"
"            if self.spec.satisfies(\"%clang@16:\") or self.spec."
"satisfies(\"%gcc@14:\"):\n"
"                flags.append(\"-Wno-error=implicit-int\")\n"
"                flags.append(\"-Wno-error=implicit-function-declaration\")\n"
"        return (flags, None, None)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:143
msgid "Understanding Spack's scope"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:145
msgid ""
"Spack is a package manager designed for performance and customization of "
"software. To clarify its role and prevent common misconceptions, it's "
"helpful to understand what falls outside of its current scope:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:148
msgid ""
"Spack is a user-space tool, not an operating system. It runs on top of your "
"existing OS (like Linux, macOS, or Windows) and complements the system's "
"native package manager (like ``yum`` or ``apt``), but does not replace it. "
"Spack relies on the host system for essentials like the C runtime libraries. "
"Building a software stack with a custom `libc` is a planned future "
"capability but is not yet implemented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../features.rst:153
msgid ""
"Spack performs native builds, not cross-compilation. It builds software for "
"the same processor architecture it is running on. Support for cross-"
"compilation (e.g., building for an ARM processor on an x86 machine) is a "
"planned future capability but is not yet implemented."
msgstr ""
